<br>
Personally I would encourage anyone to start jewelcraft as soon as they're interested. You might never make a profit with jewelry but you'll have some fun and make some friends. Crafting a friends wedding rings, for example, is very rewarding.<br>
<br>
Enchanting the bars should usually mean you make a profit when selling back to a vendor (it certainly does for gold stuff and above). But if you have a decent amount of money then you'll progress much faster if you don't bother enchanting the bars. It's a trade-off between speed of improvement and cost. Now I'm at 217 Im working with plat bars and I ALWAYS enchant the bars. In fact I spend ALL my money on bars and carry them around with me. I enchant a few whenever I have spare mana. When I get back to town (FV usually) I get all my INT and WIS gear on and start crafting the enchanted bars.<br>
<br>
Incidentally, I believe INT increases your success rate and WIS increases your chance of getting a skill improvement. Of the two I would favour INT until your jewelry skill reaches about 150. After that skill improvements come much slower so I would favour WIS.<br>
<br>
As many people have said, try to stick to crafting the next item on the triv list that isn't trivial to you yet.<br>
<br>
Expect to spend a minimum of about 5kpp on getting your skill above 200. More, depending on how many bars you enchant.<br>
<br>
Lus. <p>--<BR>
